RUN INSTRUCTIONS
Enter the directory where lab4.py and test.sh are in
Then run ./test.sh to test 3 websites and 1 print to file
Without the test, run python3 ./lab4.py -p 80 site
For the parameters -p will print to console and -f will print to a file
80 is the port and site will be the website i.e. http://google.com

QUESTIONS

1. Why did you have to encode() your request and decode() the response(s)? What do these functions do?
    Data is transfered over HTTP in bytes not plaintext, so the data sent must first be encoded.
    Then when recieving the response we must decode it so we can read it. These functions encode / decode
    plaintext into UTF-8.

2. What changes would you have to make to create a UDP socket?
    You would have to change the socket type from SOCK_STREAM to SOCK_DGRAM.

3. If you wanted to create a TCP server, what would you have to change?
    The current connection creates a socket, connects to a remote host, sends a request, and recieves a response.
    In order to make it TCP, we would have to bind to a local IP and port, Listen for a connection,
    Accept a connection, recieve data and then send a response back.

4. Can your TCP client create or process HTTPS traffic? What happens if you send a request to port 443?
    No, because we do not do the right encryption or extra steps involved in an https request. HTTPS expects
    a TLS handshake, encrypted application data, certificates and a key exchange. If I sent a request to port
    443 it wouldn't work and I wrould recieve random encrypted binary data.